r: #ccc;">story about Tether</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">President Vladimir Putin has touted a new international payments framewo=
rk to world leaders gathered in Russia this week, eager to show how he is s=
hrugging off western sanctions and challenging the US-dominated global fina=
ncial order.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Putin accused western powers o=
f =E2=80=9Cusing the dollar as a weapon=E2=80=9D, arguing in a speech at a =
Brics summit in Kazan that sanctions against Russia since its full-scale in=
vasion of Ukraine =E2=80=9Cundermine the trust in this currency and diminis=
h its powers=E2=80=9D.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main agenda item=
 of the summit, attended by the leaders of China, India, Iran and others, w=
as a Russian proposal to circumvent the US dollar by setting up a new payme=
nts messaging system known as =E2=80=9CBrics Bridge=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite the bonhomie, however, there have been=
 few practical steps towards the proposed payments system. =E2=80=A6</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main problem with the proposal is that the US=
 has made it clear to third countries that working with Russia=E2=80=99s wa=
r machine will cost them access to the dollar, hampering the Kremlin=E2=80=
=99s efforts to build a sanctions-proof payments network. ...</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The chilling effect spurred banks in countries such as=
 Turkey and China to sharply cut back on dealings with Russian counterparti=
es well beyond the executive order=E2=80=99s scope.</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No I=E2=80=99m kidding it=E2=80=99s not about Tether,=
 it=E2=80=99s about Brics Bridge, a Russian proposal to do international tr=
ade without going through the US dollar system. The problem with the US dol=
lar system, for Russia, is that the US government has a lot of control over=
 it, and uses that control to pursue its own purposes. Those purposes inclu=
de sanctioning Russia for invading Ukraine, with the result that a lot of R=
ussian politicians and companies can=E2=80=99t really use the dollar system=
.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a problem because the US d=
ollar system is widely used for international trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0includin=
g trade that does not otherwise involve the US, like Russia buying stuff fr=
om China. So Russia would like to use=C2=A0some alternative system for trad=
e with other countries. The other countries that Russia wants to trade with=
 mostly do not care about the US government=E2=80=99s geopolitical purposes=
 and would, in the abstract, be happy to trade with Russia.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=C2=A0<em>those=C2=A0</em>countries also want acc=
ess to the dollar system, because they would like to be able to trade with =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0not just the US, but all the=C2=A0<em>other </em>countries i=
n the world, which again mostly use the dollar system. So Russia=E2=80=99s =
counterparties do not want to be cut off from the dollar system like Russia=
 has been.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if Russia came to them =
and was like =E2=80=9Chey we built a new trading system, you want in,=E2=80=
=9D they will say no, because joining the new Russian trading system seems =
like an obvious way to annoy the US.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wherea=
s if some new trading system just came into being, set up by neutral third =
parties, with the properties that (1) it is not in any obvious way=C2=A0<em=
>tied to Russia=C2=A0</em>but (2) it is open to everyone and resistant to m=
eddling by the US government, then that might appeal more to Russia=E2=80=
=99s trading partners.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https:=
